<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06022228 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06022228 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Map; MAP: Associated Press. Sao Tome e Principe.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  GOVERNMENT; CHANGE; SAO-TOME-E-PRINCIPE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A newly formed opposition group ended 16 years of one-party rule by winning amajority of the vote in the first free elections in this African islandnation, officials said today.;    The Democratic Convergence Party gainedabout 55 percent of the votes in Sunday's legislative elections, according toprovisional results from the national electoral board.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  CENTER-LEFT VICTORY ENDS ISLANDS' ONE-PARTYRULE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The Movement for the Liberation of Sao Tome e Principe, which has governedthe small equatorial archipelago since independence from Portugal in 1975,received 30 percent.;    The results give the Convergence Party 31 seats inthe new 55-seat national assembly. The Movement for Liberation gained 21seats, and a third party, the Democratic Coalition, won three.;    PrimeMinister Celestino da Costa presented his resignation late Monday, and leadingparty officials pledged they will form &quot;a civilized opposition.&quot;;    Sao Tomee Principe is the second African nation in a week to defeat longtime rulers atthe polls.;    On Jan. 13, Cape Verde's main opposition party gained alandslide legislative election victory.;    The Convergence Party, whichclaims a center-left position, is expected to name economist Leonel Mario deAlva, 55, as prime minister. De Alva is a former premier and foreign ministerwho broke with the governing party in 1982.;    He returned from exile in CapeVerde in 1990 to help found the party.;    The Movement for Liberation droppedits Marxist stance last year and now professes a social democratic program.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  SAO TOME, Sao Tome e Principe  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910122  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  MAP  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  245  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday January 22, 199100022228,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>